        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The object is distant and we can expect broad lines. We request a bandwith of 1875 MHz and a channel spacing of 15.6 MHz. This will simultaneously maximise the SNR per resolution element while easily resolving the line profiles with a velocity resolution of 24 km/s. Note that even if the lines are much more narrow than assumed, this velocity resolution should be sufficient to resolve them.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>An HST I-band image shows that the minimal separation the individual objects can be clearly separated with an angular resolution of 0.2". We therefore request obsevations at least at this resolution level.

The most extended object in our field has an angular scale 0.8", well under the filtering threshold for the requested observation mode. We therefore do not require ACA observations.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We have first carried out SED modelling showing that the total SFR of the system is of the order of 1300 Msun/yr. We have converted this SFR to a CII line luminosity using the relation of Herrera-Camus et al. (2015). Using the HST I band image we have estimated the emission area for each object, leading to a minimum CII line flux of 3.25 Jy km/s per beam. Assuming a maximum line width of 1000 km/s, this corresponds to a flux density of 3.25 mJy per beam. The determination of the line profile requires a detection at least at the 5 sigma level. We therefore require a sensitivity of 0.65 mJy per beam.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
