    <prp:abstract>One of most puzzling aspects of galaxy evolution is the tight correlation between BH (black hole) mass and some of the galaxy properties. This correlation strongly suggests a physical connection between the central BH and galaxy-wide star formation. This proposal aims at better understanding why and how BH grow at high redshift (z&gt;2), in relation with the cosmological evolution of galaxies. The high-redshift range is especially important to constrain the co-evolution of galaxies and BH as we expect the transition between the heavily-enshrouded high-accretion phase and the blow-out phase to occur during this period. We have identified an ideal LBG target to investigate co-evolution at z=3.86. It appears to simultaneously exhibit strong BH growth and massive star formation, with an exceptional amount of dust (&lt;1% of LBGs are detected in FIR). Our objectives are: 1. confirm the redshift of the IR counterparts, 2. understand the nature of the components that form this system, 3. reassess dust attenuation at high redshift, 4. confirm or infirm that we are witnessing the early phase of the co-evolution of BH and galaxies, and 5. estimate the BH mass and constrain its growth rate.</prp:abstract>
